2023 updates (video 1/2)

2022 was a polarizing year for me on and off the golf course. It was the best and also the worst year of my life. 

I travelled all over the world to play in dozens of golf tournaments and played in Q school for the first time for the Korn Ferry Tour and also DP World Tour. I accomplished a huge goal of mine by funding my way though all this off the strength of my personal brand on social media, but it was disappointing to not shoot low enough scores to keep the money in the bank and buy myself more time to keep improving and more chances at Q schools and tournaments. 

However, I have gained immense clarity on who I am and why I am on this earth and none of that would have been possible without risking everything this past decade to design a life that made sense to me, even if it didn’t make sense to anyone else. 

A life centered around expanding my mind and comfort zone through new experiences and dropping my shoulder into the things that scare me most. You will notice a shift in my online and real world aura and communication style in 2023 and my hope is that is resonates with some of you who have followed for years and also with a new audience, and over time I can create a catalog of educational and helpful content based on my unrelenting pursuit of the good life through combining my passion for golf, health, and overall human improvement. 

A life where I live in total unison of thought, word and action all day every day, and routinely have peak experiences that open my mind and consciousness to levels I previously thought were impossible. 

My primary curiosity lies in understanding:
-how to live the best life possible by maximizing human potential in every area
-seeking deeper meaning and purpose in life, understanding why we are here
-returning to competitive golf as an evolved and more conscious human to test my hypothesis that I can qualify for and retain status on a world tour once I do more inner work related to personal development.

2023 updates (video 2/2)

…Caption continued from video 1/2…

I am essentially turning myself into a test dummy with all these different self improvement modalities like ice baths, meditating, fasting, sauna, breath work, nutrition, etc, all aimed at achieving higher consciousness and a more fulfilling human experience, first to fill up my own cup and then to let it overflow for the benefit of others.

I will pass on my findings via content and courses by aggregating my research, noting what worked and what didn’t work, and ultimately streamlining the process of improving oneself in all areas, including golf.

I will make seemingly complex subjects and principles seem cool and more easily understandable by relating them to common goals many of us share with golf, fitness, and mental health, as well as continually improving my cinematics and editing to make my content more enjoyable to watch.

Creating content about my progression towards these goals will amplify how serious I take my own journey because I want to put my best foot forward for those watching and be a positive role model for the next generation.

I’m essentially thinking of my accounts as a new age school where the goal is to give relevant, understandable, and actionable advice on areas of life I have experience with. 

I will blend elements of philosophy, psychology, spirituality, peak performance and golf to share my unique perspective and worldview, tying golf to other subjects I find fascinating that others may have never considered. This is how I will differentiate my brand and value from those who specialize in one subject or another but leave out the interplay between them all.

Excited for another year of growth and progression. Thank you all for your constant support, without it none of this would be possible.

Self discipline: the ability to control one’s feelings and overcome one’s weaknesses; the ability to pursue what one thinks is right despite temptations to abandon it.

I believe developing self discipline is one of the fundamentals to success no matter what your goals are in life. The more hard things you do, the more discipline you will develop. 

Start small: give up soda or sweets for a day, go to the gym when you’re tired, put one hour into your side business even if it means giving up something else. Your future self is watching every move you make and begging you to become the person you were meant to be.

4 Reasons EVERY Golfer Should Start Meditating (read more ⬇️) 

1. Increased Focus + Concentration: 
- As you sit and attempt to focus on your breath, you will inevitably be distracted by thoughts coming and going from your mind. 
- Every time you recognize you were distracted by a thought or feeling, gently nudge your focus back to the breath.
- This is like a bicep curl for your mind. With practice, you become more resilient to distractions from your own mind as well as the external world.
- This leads to a deeper concentration and present state of mind when planning and executing golf shots.

2. Improved Mental Toughness: 
- Studies have shown that a regular meditation practice could help you regulate your emotions and not get emotionally reactive in challenging or taxing situations. 
- This results from the increased size and strength of the prefrontal cortex, the area of the brain associated with resilience and mental toughness.

3. Better Sleep Quality: 
- Golfers need to get adequate sleep to perform well. Meditation can help golfers relax and achieve a deeper level of sleep, which can lead to improved performance on the course.
- Studies have found that meditation can help reduce cortisol, which is the hormone associated with stress. Meditation also increases natural melatonin levels to help with more restful sleep.

4. Reduced Anxiety + Stress: 
- Anxiety and stress can manifest physically in the form of tension, shakiness and loss of strength and power
- As you become more self aware, mindful and present through consistent meditation, it becomes easier to disconnect from the thoughts and feelings you experience and remain focused on the task or shot at hand.
- Simply bringing awareness to your experience in the present moment helps you to feel less controlled by your emotions and thoughts. You begin to recognize that feelings come and go and you can choose whether or not to attach to them based on which ones do and don’t serve you.

There are many forms of meditation, but if you are new to it I would recommend starting with a guided app or video on YouTube. I love using @fitmind , and have also used @headspace quite a bit. Good luck!

We become what we think about most of the time💭
.
.
Our thoughts become our words which become our actions, and whatever actions we consistently repeat shape the person we become.
.
.
If you want your daily thoughts to align with your goals and highest values, go on a mental diet. Starve yourself from all negativity, gossip, news and pop culture, both online and in real life. Instead, plant seeds and water the garden of your mind with inspirational and educational podcasts, YouTube channels, courses, books, and conversations with like minded people. 
.
.
I think most of us fail to realize that the majority of our thoughts are not actually ‘our’ thoughts at all, rather they are a regurgitation of the most recent information we have consumed. So if you want to encourage your mind to think about things that lead to progress and fulfillment, find others who are already talking about and living the life you want to live, and spend time with them either in the real world or by consuming their content. Once you begin this process, the algorithms will work in your favor and start suggesting countless accounts talking about similar topics that you may find interesting and inspirational.
.
.
I’d recommend starting with unfollowing or muting any social media accounts that don’t add value to your life or relate to your goals. Once you create some space from the addictive cycle of keeping up with the Jones’s, replace them with a few accounts that inspire you to take action towards your goals. Hope this works for some of you, it has really been life changing for me.

Why You’ll NEVER Play Your Best Golf (until you fix your poor mental health)⬇️⬇️

I want to share a short story about my experience with the correlation between golf scores and mental health: 

In 2016, after 2 years off from golf due to an injury, I was finally healthy enough to begin practicing again. One month later, I won my first pro tournament. 
 
How could this be possible? I hadn’t practiced for years and I wasn’t even able to exercise. I had been going through stem cell injections and recovering on a sofa while my competitors were out practicing the past 2 years. 

I believe it was because my attitude and perspective on life (aka mental health) was at an all time high. After being told by several doctors I would never be able to swing a club again, the overwhelming gratitude I felt once I defied the odds and returned to golf made up for my lack of practice.

The joy I felt by simply being on a golf course again overshadowed what I was lacking physically. I was completely present and accessing a flow state on the golf course I had never experienced before. 

My mind was free of negative thoughts about bad bounces, missed putts, and what score I was shooting. I was consumed with appreciation for a second chance at golf and I was overflowing with energy, enthusiasm, and positivity.

Unfortunately, over the years this feeling has faded. Although I have practiced thousands of hours and played hundreds of tournaments since 2016, I haven’t been able to access that same flow state very often, and my performance has suffered. I slowly lost the mental edge I had gained from the challenging experience I went through, and have been experimenting with tools and tactics to improve my mental health since then. 

My journey is ongoing, and my ideas about how to achieve my goals in golf and life may not work for everyone, but I hope to continue validating my theories over time by getting results in my own life, and I hope those of you facing similar roadblocks to your goals will be able to skillfully navigate around them using my content as a guide.

Things I Wish I Knew At The Start Of My Golfing Journey (Part 1)

1️⃣ Practice putting more than anything (if you want to shoot your best scores)

Great putting can make up for just about anything. 

If you have 2 hours to practice on a given day, I’d recommend spending an hour and fifteen minutes of it putting, then spend the remainder on the range or chipping. 

2️⃣ Don’t bring expectations to the golf course

Thinking that you will shoot a good score today because you shot a good score yesterday is the best way to not shoot a good score today. 

No two rounds of golf or shots are the same, and comparison is the thief of joy both in golf and life. 

Good golf requires total acceptance of all outcomes, good and bad, and the less judgmental you can be the more you will enjoy the game (hint: this will lead to better shots and lower scores too)

3️⃣ You’ll rise (or fall) to the level of those you play/practice with

Choose your golf circle according to the goals you have with the game.

 If you just want to have fun, pick a fun crowd. 

But if you want to compete on your high school or college team, or play in amateur or pro tournaments after school, I’d recommend befriending the guys or girls on a similar path who share the same goals as you.

If you want to get better at anything in life, proactively place yourself in environments where you are the small fish in a big pond. If you only hang in circles where you’re the top dog, you’ll never be challenged to grow into anything more than you currently are.

The times I’ve improved most rapidly at golf have been the times when I was on tour with guys for months at a time who were better than me. 

You not only get better by competing against people who routinely beat you, but you also pick up small, intangible things from them. 

Their aura and confidence can rub off on you if you’re perceptive to their energy and pay attention to the subtle differences between you and them.

In a confusing world full of hacks, quick fixes, and instant gratification pitfalls, the truth is that good habits repeated consistently over time will eventually lead to greatness in any field. 

It’s more fun for our little dopamine chasing monkey minds to constantly seek new information and search for shortcuts to the good life, but sticking to the fundamentals is how all the greats built their empires. 

Go slow to go fast. 

Here’s a step by step formula to achieve just about anything in life:

1️⃣ Clearly define a goal

2️⃣ Determine the daily actions that will lead to that goal (study someone who has already achieved that goal if you aren’t sure what these actions are) 

3️⃣ Repeat these actions daily and ignore results. Don’t look up until you have hit your goals. 

You will be tempted to switch paths if you aren’t seeing results in a few weeks or months. In most cases, you simply haven’t put enough time in to deserve the results. 

Be patient, trust the process, and ignore anyone who tries to convince you to deviate from the path for a quick fix or hack. 

Anything worth doing takes time. You got this🤝

These 9 habits will TRANSFORM your golf game (read more⬇️)

1️⃣ COLD SHOWERS + ICE BATHS

These reduce inflammation and anxiety, and strengthen your discipline muscle.

2️⃣ MEDITATION 
 
Improves ability to remain calm and make decisions on the golf course based on logic rather than emotion.

3️⃣ EXERCISE 
 
Frequent exercise leads to more energy, better sleep, and improved mental health.

It doesn’t have to be in the gym either: go for a walk, bike ride, swim, or hike if you enjoy those activities. 

4️⃣ EAT CLEAN + HYDRATE
 
Avoid processed foods, added sugars or artificial sweeteners, and eat until you feel 80% full usually.

Lots of protein and veggies.

5️⃣ RECOVERY
 
Mobility work before and after golf goes a long way for reducing soreness and risk of injury.

Advanced level: Check out @hyperice Normatec leg sleeves or Hypervolt Go 2 if you’re really training hard and need quicker recovery.

6️⃣ OPTIMIZE YOUR SLEEP

Avoid caffeine after 2 pm.
 
Wake up and go to bed at the same time every day.
 
Turn thermostat below 68 degrees.

Read before bed to fall asleep easier.

7️⃣ GRATITUDE JOURNALING
 
Writing 3 things you’re grateful for each morning trains your brain to look for positives throughout your day.

This translates to a better attitude on the golf course and more resilience when faced with adversity.

8️⃣ BREATHWORK 
 
Breathwork can help center you in the present moment and reduce mind racing. 
 
I prefer to take 5-10 breaths between most shots when I’m playing golf to constantly ground myself and eliminate unnecessary mental chatter about past and future. 

@iceman_hof and DMT breathing are my two favorite methods.

9️⃣ RESET YOUR DOPAMINE 

The constant overstimulation we expose ourselves to is aging us rapidly and making us literally dumber and slower at everything.
 
Once a week, do a dopamine detox/no phone day to combat this.

The more bored you can be, the better, so spend some time alone, go for a walk, read a book, journal, or even stare at a wall for an hour (seriously, it will actually help).

Things I wish I knew at the start of my golf journey (part 2) (read more⬇️)

1️⃣ Don’t be afraid to compete:

You learn more from competition than practice. 

When you’re under pressure your tendencies and weaknesses will get exposed. 

This is good, because without awareness we can’t begin to fix them. 

If you spend all your time on the range you rob yourself of the opportunity to fail, learn, and eventually improve. 

2️⃣ Chase progress not perfection:

Perfection is not attainable in golf, the sooner you accept this the better.

The goal is to get the ball in the hole in the fewest amount of strokes possible and some days it will look prettier than others.

Learn to accept all outcomes on the course and judge your success based off attitude and effort rather than results.

3️⃣ Increasing your confidence off the golf course will increase your confidence on the course:

For example: getting in better shape, giving your best to school, work, relationships, breaking out of your comfort zone by trying new things, asking the girl out, etc.) 

Golf is not a separate entity from life. They have a symbiotic relationship. If you improve one you improve the other.

If you get jacked, get a promotion at work, or hit a record high month of sales in your business, I guarantee that extra swag you feel from the success will trickle into your golf game.

Keeping this in mind, you should always have an arena outside of golf you are learning about and pursuing goals in.

1. Taking 6 breaths in between every shot

There’s research explaining the significance behind taking 6 breaths if you want to look it up, but it basically: 

-Calms your nerves

I’m spending more time with my own thoughts and getting to know myself better, which makes it easier to navigate my thoughts during a round of golf.

There is plenty more research explaining the benefits of meditation and how it correlates to playing your best golf but these are just some of my own reflections after a few weeks of really committing more to my practice. 

3. Getting more high quality sleep 

Sleep has the greatest impact on every function of the body and mind, without adequate rest we simply cannot perform at our best, no matter how good our diet, practice, and workouts are.

I’ve been getting sunlight immediately upon waking every morning by going for a short walk. 

This is proven to release serotonin and improve mood for the day and is also effective against insomnia.

In short, getting a few minutes of direct sun exposure first thing sets your bodies internal clock to be ready for sleep 14-16 hours later which is what we want.

I played in another Bo Tour event yesterday at El Dorado GC and shot 76 (+4). I finished T10th and 1 stroke outside of a paycheck. Here are my 3 main takeaways from the day:

1. Never make assumptions about where you are in the pack:

I was leading the tournament through 6 holes but thought I was probably a few back. 

After double bogeying the 7th hole, I falsely assumed it put me 4 or 5 shots back of the lead when in fact I was only 1 or 2 off.

Had I stuck to the game plan rather than feeling the need to press and catch up, I still would have been in contention down the last few holes.

2. Bad sleep leads to bad golf:

The amount of sleep I’ve been getting directly correlates to my adaptability and composure on the course. 

If I’m fully rested it makes me almost unphase-able out there. 

If I’m under-rested, it’s typically only a matter of time before I snap and spiral downward. 

I lost my temper a few times yesterday which clouded my perception of reality and drained vital energy I should have directed at closing out the round as strong as possible in spite of the mistakes I made.

3. Talk to yourself like you are your own best friend/caddy:

Berating yourself serves no purpose and once you begin to release negative chemicals like cortisol, they stay in your system for hours, making it impossible to play your best golf. 

Talk to yourself like you would talk to 10 year old you. 

Be kind, encouraging, and optimistic at all times and you’ll get more out of yourself.

1️⃣ Track stats when you play so you know what to practice:

Some of the most common stat tracking systems are @decade_golf, @upgameapp , @strokesgainedgolf, and @georgegankasgolf membership website. 

If you’re a beginner, start by counting how many fairways and greens in regulation you hit per round and where your misses were.

Also track the distance of your first putt on every green and the number of putts, then google “strokes gained putting calculator” and enter your stats there.

The point of this is to start collecting data to identify our strengths and weaknesses so we can allocate our practice time effectively.

2️⃣ Consistent daily practice beats marathon sessions once a week:

The tortoise always beats the hair. 

It may be well intentioned to work long hours on your swing hitting 400 balls on the weekend, but this isn’t something most people could remain consistent with day in and day out. 

You’ll get sore and need a few days off, and you might even ingrain bad habits by playing while extremely fatigued. 

A better approach would be to devote an hour a day to getting a few swings and putts in, or even just swinging a club in your living room for 5 minutes in the evenings.

3️⃣ Getting fit for clubs is more important than working on your swing:

Most people severely underestimate the value of a good club fitter and builder. 

They think they need to “fix” their swing before it is “worth it” to get fit for clubs. 

This thinking is actually backwards. 

Once you are fit into the proper clubs: length, flex, lie angle, loft, club head type, and swing weight, you may find you don’t need to change as much about your swing as you thought you did. 

Sometimes we are compensating in our swing for poorly fit clubs.

For most beginner and intermediate golfers, the club fitting process is going to yield more ROI than lessons. 

My good friend @matched_up_golf is one of the best fitters and builders in the business and has been working with me for a decade on every club in my bag. 

There’s no one I trust more and if you’re thinking of getting fitted do yourself a favor and DM @matched_up_golf or call @foreward.golf

3 things that have helped me get more out of my practice (read more⬇️)

1️⃣ Writing out a plan for what specific drills or parts of the game I will practice and for how long before I even get to the course. 

This ensures I have a purpose for being at the course and make the most of my time while I’m there, and also keeps me more engaged throughout my practice session.

2️⃣ Time yourself: spend half of your practice session putting and chipping. 

These areas require the most practice time to have great touch and also will shave more strokes off your score than anything else.

3️⃣ Leave your phone in your bag (or better yet your car) except for when filming your swing. 

Our cell phone is the single greatest distraction preventing us from reaching most of our goals. It will be painful to detach from it at first, but pretty soon you will start to enjoy the heightened sense of presence you can apply to whatever you’re doing in life, and the improved results that will come along with it can. 

It’s far more rewarding to actually preserve your brain power and energy for your goals in life and begin achieving them as a result of better time management than it is to drown in unearned cheap dopamine by scrolling on your phone all day every day, procrastinating on the tasks you know will move your life forward the most. This applies to golf and pretty much everything else in life in my experience.

Golfweek ranked Circling Raven the No. 1 Public Course in Idaho in 2023 for the 12th time.

Owned by the Coeur d’Alene Tribe, Circling Raven’s 18 holes span 620 stunning acres of Palouse terrain. 

The tribe wanted its golf course architect, Gene Bates, to let the land dictate where the holes should be located.

Named after a seminal tribal chief, the course sits amid woodlands, wetlands, and wildlife, including eagles and moose. 
 
In addition to being rated No. 1 in Idaho, the course is regularly ranked among the country’s best in Resort Course, Casino Course, Pro Shop and other best-in-kind categories. 

It will host the Circling Raven Championship, an Epson “Road to the LPGA” Tour event, August 21-27. 

After golf options include the 15,000-square-foot spa voted 1st for “Resort Spas that deliver the Ahh Factor’’ by Spatrips.com (2012), an award-winning casino, multiple restaurants and bars, and live entertainment and shows. 

Named Tribal Destination of the Year in 2019 by AIANTA and winning the silver Distinguished Dozen award from Courier in 2019 and 2020, the property features 300 rooms and suites, seven distinct food and beverage venues and hands-on tours and experiences through the casino’s Cultural Tourism Program. 
 
And through the casino, the tribe has donated more than $33 million to local, state, and regional educational institutions or initiatives.
 
The mantra at the property is “Welcome Home” as the tribe is known for it hospitality and service to others. 

After experiencing this hospitality first hand at the golf course, resort, spa, and restaurants, I can’t recommend @circlingravengolfclub and @cdacasino highly enough. 

This place is a must-add to your bucket list!

*repost (sometimes we need reminders more than we need new info) 

I want to share a story about my experience with the correlation between golf scores and mental health: 

In 2016, after 2 years off from golf due to an injury, I was finally healthy enough to begin practicing again. One month later, I won my first pro tournament. 
 
How could this be possible? I hadn’t practiced for years and I wasn’t even able to exercise. I had been going through stem cell injections and recovering on a sofa while my competitors were out practicing the past 2 years. 

I believe it was because my attitude and perspective on life (mental health) was at an all time high. After being told by several doctors I would never swing a club again, the overwhelming gratitude I felt once I defied the odds and returned to golf made up for my lack of practice.

The joy of simply being on a golf course again overshadowed what I was lacking physically. I was completely present and accessing a flow state on the golf course I had never experienced before. 

My mind was free of negative thoughts about bad bounces, missed putts, and what score I was shooting. I was consumed with appreciation for a second chance at golf and I was overflowing with energy, enthusiasm, and positivity.

Unfortunately, over the years this feeling has faded. Although I have practiced thousands of hours and played hundreds of tournaments since 2016, I haven’t been able to access that same flow state very often, and my performance has suffered. I slowly lost the mental edge I had gained from the challenging experience I went through, and have been experimenting with tools and tactics to improve my mental health since then. 

My journey is ongoing, and my ideas about how to achieve my goals in golf and life may not work for everyone, but I hope to continue validating my theories over time by getting results in my own life, and I hope those of you facing similar roadblocks to your goals will be able to navigate them using my content as a guide.

1️⃣ COLD SHOWERS + ICE BATHS

These reduce inflammation and anxiety, and strengthen your discipline muscle.

2️⃣ MEDITATION 
 
Improves ability to remain calm and make decisions on the golf course based on logic rather than emotion.

3️⃣ EXERCISE 
 
Frequent exercise leads to more energy, better sleep, and improved mental health.

It doesn’t have to be in the gym either: go for a walk, bike ride, swim, or hike if you enjoy those activities. 

4️⃣ EAT CLEAN + HYDRATE
 
Avoid processed foods, added sugars or artificial sweeteners, and eat until you feel 80% full usually.

Lots of protein and veggies.

Mobility work before and after golf goes a long way for reducing soreness and risk of injury.

Advanced level: Check out @hyperice Normatec leg sleeves or Hypervolt Go 2 if you’re really training hard and need quicker recovery.

6️⃣ OPTIMIZE YOUR SLEEP

Avoid caffeine after 2 pm.
 
Wake up and go to bed at the same time every day.
 
Turn thermostat below 68 degrees.

Read before bed to fall asleep easier.

7️⃣ GRATITUDE JOURNALING
 
Writing 3 things you’re grateful for each morning trains your brain to look for positives throughout your day.

This translates to a better attitude on the golf course and more resilience when faced with adversity.

8️⃣ BREATHWORK 
 
Breathwork can help center you in the present moment and reduce mind racing. 
 
I prefer to take 5-10 breaths between most shots when I’m playing golf to constantly ground myself and eliminate unnecessary mental chatter about past and future. 

@iceman_hof and DMT breathing are my two favorite methods.

The constant overstimulation we expose ourselves to is aging us rapidly and making us literally dumber and slower at everything.
 
Once a week, do a dopamine detox/no phone day to combat this.

The more bored you can be, the better, so spend some time alone, go for a walk, read a book, journal, or even stare at a wall for an hour (seriously, it will actually help).

👋🏽If you’re new to golf and stumbled upon this post, congrats! You just saved yourself a lot of frustration (trust me, I made all these mistakes before🤦🏼‍♂️

1️⃣Hitting the same club at the same target repeatedly:

We don’t get to hit the same shot twice on the golf course, so why practice like this on the driving range?

Ask yourself: “Do I want to be a great driving range golfer or a great on-course golfer?”

I’d suggest changing clubs and targets frequently on the driving range.

The more often you change these 2 variables, the more prepared and adaptable you will be during an actual round of golf, resulting in consistently lower scores and more fun.

2️⃣ Going to the driving range but never actually playing:

I see most new golfers spend 90% of their time on the range and rarely play 9 or 18.

If the goal is to shoot lower scores on the course, it only makes sense to spend the majority of our time practicing on the course.

Learning to deal with the unpredictable nature of a round of golf is uncomfortable at first, but exactly what makes us better players in the long
run.

Always staying in a controlled environment like the driving range will never allow us to reach our full potential.

3️⃣ Never practicing putting:

Most would agree it’s more fun to swing out of your shoes at the driver on the range than it is to hit 3 foot putts on the practice green.

Most would also agree that it’s more fun to shoot lower scores.

Putting is the unlock.

According to the USA, the average golfer hits 40 putts per round which accounts for nearly half their total strokes.

If shooting lower scores is the goal, nothing will have a bigger impact on that than improving at putting.
Putting practice doesn’t have to be boring though.

Listen to music or a podcast while doing tee drills or using a putting mat for 30 minutes

Compete against a friend for low overall score in a 9 or 18 hole game

Or google “best putting drills/games” and find something that sounds fun, your golf scores will thank you.

If you’re interested in learning more, join my broadcast channel linked in my b1o where I share what’s working for me on and off the golf course.

If I could tell my younger self 3 things about golf, it would be this ↓

1️⃣ Practice putting more than anything (if you want to shoot your best scores)

Great putting can make up for just about anything. 

If you have 2 hours to practice on a given day, I’d recommend spending an hour and fifteen minutes of it putting, then spend the remainder on the range or chipping. 

2️⃣ Don’t bring expectations to the golf course

Thinking that you will shoot a good score today because you shot a good score yesterday is the best way to not shoot a good score today. 

No two rounds of golf or shots are the same, and comparison is the thief of joy both in golf and life. 

Good golf requires total acceptance of all outcomes, good and bad, and the less judgmental you can be the more you will enjoy the game (hint: this will lead to better shots and lower scores too)

3️⃣ You’ll rise (or fall) to the level of those you play/practice with

Choose your golf circle according to the goals you have with the game.

 If you just want to have fun, pick a fun crowd. 

But if you want to compete on your high school or college team, or play in amateur or pro tournaments after school, I’d recommend befriending the guys or girls on a similar path who share the same goals as you.

If you want to get better at anything in life, proactively place yourself in environments where you are the small fish in a big pond. If you only hang in circles where you’re the top dog, you’ll never be challenged to grow into anything more than you currently are.

The times I’ve improved most rapidly at golf have been the times when I was on tour with guys for months at a time who were better than me. 

You not only get better by competing against people who routinely beat you, but you also pick up small, intangible things from them. 

Their aura and confidence can rub off on you if you’re perceptive to their energy and pay attention to the subtle differences between you and them.

Underrated habits for success⬇️

1️⃣Plan your days the night before:

✍🏼Decide when, where and what you are going to do each day ahead of time (write it down)

🔁Replace “I will work tomorrow morning” with “I will film from 9-10, edit from 10-12 and write captions and post 2 videos from 12-1.”

The world is littered with distractions and if we don’t proactively take control of each hour of the day, it’s easy to float along and wind up at a completely different destination than we intended

2️⃣Prioritize sleep above everything else:

⏰Set an alarm for bed time as well as wake up time so your body can get into a rhythm and start to get deeper sleep

🤳No phone for the first and last hour of each day, these are important hours for planning and reflection and being on our phone before bed is hyper stimulating and makes it harder to fall asleep

☀️Get outside in the sunlight (or clouds) immediately each morning for a 5 minute walk, this resets your circadian rhythm and signals to your body that it’s time to wake up, and also will help you to get tired naturally about 16 hours later for bed

3️⃣Control what you consume:

🍎Food: the biggest factor affecting our mood and energy levels

Keep it simple by eating as many single ingredient foods as possible (ex: potato, chicken, fruits, veggies, rice, steak) 

💻Information:

Stop consuming content that is irrelevant to your goals 

Follow and engage with accounts that remind you of the person you want to become in all areas (health, wealth, relationships, happiness)

🚫Unfollow or mute accounts promoting negativity, drama, or anything not related to your goals, curiosities, and passions

Probably 90% of the thoughts we have are not our own but rather a regurgitation of something we heard someone else say, so make sure you filter what comes into your awareness field carefully and understand the quality of your future thoughts, ideas, and actions is only as good as the quality of what you let in

⭕️Social circle:

Pay attention to how you feel after spending time with people. Do you feel energized and light? Or drained and tense?

Align yourself with people who remind you of your ideal future self

#success #habits

1️⃣Track stats when you play so you know what to practice:

Some of the most common stat tracking systems are @decade_golf, @upgameapp , @strokesgainedgolf, and @georgegankasgolf membership website. 

If you’re a beginner, start by counting how many fairways and greens in regulation you hit per round and where your misses were.

Also track the distance of your first putt on every green and the number of putts, then google “strokes gained putting calculator” and enter your stats there.

The point of this is to start collecting data to identify our strengths and weaknesses so we can allocate our practice time effectively.

2️⃣Consistent daily practice beats marathon sessions once a week:

The tortoise always beats the hair. 

It may be well intentioned to work long hours on your swing hitting 400 balls on the weekend, but this isn’t something most people could remain consistent with day in and day out. 

You’ll get sore and need a few days off, and you might even ingrain bad habits by playing while extremely fatigued. 

A better approach would be to devote an hour a day to getting a few swings and putts in, or even just swinging a club in your living room for 5 minutes in the evenings.

3️⃣Getting fit for clubs is more important than working on your swing:

Most people severely underestimate the value of a good club fitter and builder. 

They think they need to “fix” their swing before it is “worth it” to get fit for clubs. 

This thinking is actually backwards. 

Once you are fit into the proper clubs: length, flex, lie angle, loft, club head type, and swing weight, you may find you don’t need to change as much about your swing as you thought you did. 

Sometimes we are compensating in our swing for poorly fit clubs.

For most beginner and intermediate golfers, the club fitting process is going to yield more ROI than lessons. 

My good friend @matched_up_golf is one of the best fitters and builders in the business and has been working with me for a decade on every club in my bag. 

There’s no one I trust more and if you’re thinking of getting fitted do yourself a favor and DM @matched_up_golf or @foreward.golf

⚠️ ATTENTION GOLFERS ⚠️ 

This is a challenge to get your golf game and mindset dialed before the new year. While everyone else takes time off, let’s build momentum and start 2024 hot. Whether you play professionally, in high school, college, or just for fun on the weekends with friends, we all want to shoot better scores. Let me help. 

If you can make the right habits automatic, you will see rapid progress. The quickest way I’ve found to create behavior change is to join a group where that behavior is the norm and expected, aka social pressure. As a basic survival mechanism, humans adapt and fit in to their environments, so choosing the right one is your greatest task on the path to growth. 

For instance, I’ve noticed that whenever I spend a summer on the Dakotas Tour and am traveling with 100 other high level professionals to the same tournaments for 3 months, I step up big time with my golf practice and training. I rise to their level of practicing/playing every day. It is exhausting, but the more you do, the more you can do. 

I usually progress more with my golf game in those 3 months than I do the rest of the year when I just practice on my own. Let this challenge have that same affect on you, and lets all push each other to be better. 

THE RULES:

Golf
* 5 large buckets/week
* putt + chip 1 hour/day
* 9 holes 3x/week
* write goals for practice sessions

Physical Health
* workout 3x/week
* stretch 15 mins/day
* walk 30 mins/day
* no junk food, less sugar, more veggies
* gallon H20/day

Mental health
* gratitude journal 
* meditate 5 mins/day
* no phone 1 hour before bed + after waking
* read 10 pages
* sleep 8+ hours

Is this you? 🫵🏽 I’m not ashamed to admit it’s been me many times before. 

When you’re making changes and improvements to your life, it can be very exciting and we naturally want to share our excitement with others. 

The danger with this lies in the fact that our brain floods with dopamine when we talk about our goals and visions for the future. It almost feels as though we are accomplishing our goals by simply talking about them and envisioning our ideal future. 

This release of unearned dopamine drains our motivation to actually take action and do the hard work necessary to achieve our goals. 

I’m certainly a believer in visualization and manifestation and I’m not against sharing your goals and wins with others for accountability and building community, but I would just offer a word of caution from my personal experience to focus more of your attention on action and less on talk to make sure you are becoming the person you actually want to be.🤝

Don’t let anyone who hasn’t gone where you want to go tell you what you can’t do.

Your environment dictates who you become. 

Curate an environment in support of your goals, not opposing them. 

If you have to rely on willpower to go against the grain of your environment, eventually your willpower will run out and you’ll revert back to the expected behaviors and habits of the people in your environment. 

We all seek social validation by imitating the behavior of those closest to us.

So why not make this work to our advantage by surrounding ourselves with people already living the life we envision for our future selves?

Find people with shared interests, preferably a few steps ahead of you, and challenge yourself to rise to their level and imitate their habits.

Don’t go towards the easy crowds where you feel like the biggest fish in the pond, there’s no growth in that

Why are you still reading? 

Obviously some of what I’m saying resonates with you.

Take these words and the impossible chance that you found this post as a sign to begin creating an environment in support of your goals. 

Your environment includes who you follow and consume content from also, so consider following me if you want more reminders like this one.

7 steps to achieve any goal:

1. Clearly define a goal (what you want)

2. Clearly define why you want it
 (pro tip: ask yourself why you want what you want 7 times to get to the core reasoning that will keep you motivated when you feel like giving up) 

Example: I want to grow an audience of 1M on instagram by 2025

Why? To encourage people to improve their lives and raise the collective consciousness

Why? Because in order to lead a community down a path of self improvement, I must embody a life of growth to be an authentic and credible leader for them. It is important to me to practice my leadership skills 

Why? Because one day I want to lead my children to be good people who have a positive impact in the world and leading a community on social media is good practice. 

Why? Because I believe fatherhood will be my single greatest role in life and I want to be as prepared as possible beforehand 

Basically we just boiled down a superficial goal of gaining followers to a much deeper goal of preparing to be a great father who leads by example. Having framed my goal in this new way will make it much easier to stay committed when times get tough.

3. Invest in yourself and your goal (buy courses, a coach, go to a workshop, etc)

4. Make it public by sharing this goal with your family, friends, partner, etc (social pressure helps us stay accountable)

5. Set deadlines to complete different actions that will lead to your long term goal

6. Install several forms of feedback/accountability (coaching, working with others with same goals, tracking your daily actions and progress in a journal)

7. Remove everything from your environment opposing your goals

New Years in Mexico dump⬇️ 

I was on a meditation retreat for the last week @mardejade_retreat and went completely off grid.

We spent most of our time learning and practicing Vedic meditation and rounding (3rd slide) with @lightwatkins , a practice combining meditation, yoga, and breathwork designed to supercharge stress release and deeply rest the nervous system.

We ate only organic food grown at a farm on site and I followed a strict vegetarian diet all week to help my nervous system down regulate and conserve the energy that would normally go into digesting meat for my mind, body, and soul to rest and heal.

We had a beautiful New Year’s Eve ritual where we wrote down things we wanted to leave in the past and burned them in a bonfire and also wrote down things we want to manifest in 2024 and planted the paper in a garden with seeds wrapped inside.

I also was able to participate in a traditional sweat lodge ceremony and tried acupuncture to aid in the stress release process, along with lots of journaling and time in nature.

My ultimate goal for the week was to spend time in total silence and deal with whatever came up in my mind and soul, tuning out the noise from the external world so I could tune into my own inner guidance and heart.

I feel like I was successful in this and am stepping into a new year recharged and rested with a clear mission and purpose. 

It was extremely challenging to turn the focus inward for so long with zero distractions because a lot of emotions, past trauma, and stress triggers can come up when you remain still for this long, but allowing yourself space to feel these things fully is essential if you ever want to let go of them and move forward in life with an open heart.

I’m proud of myself for not running back to the comfort of distraction (aka social media, TV, friends, work, junk food) and instead leaning into the fear of the unknown internal world and allowing myself to have whatever experience I needed to have without judgment or expectation of what should be happening.

I can’t wait to continue on this journey of self discovery and keep sharing what’s working for me with you all.

Happy 2024, let’s get it🎇
